Green carbon-based materials such as nanotubes, carbon-dots, etc. are ideal candidates for fabricating sensors for detecting hazardous environmental pollutants [Fig. 2
                     ] When reductive molecules such as NO2 are present in the environment, the electrical conductance of these materials increases, hence adsorbing NO2 molecules on their surface [12]. The selectivity, sensitivity, and performance of these carbon materials as sensors can be enhanced by modifying their surface with various functional groups. This process is known as functionalization. Carbon-based materials can be functionalized either through covalent or non-covalent surface modifications Non-covalent methods generally consist of modifying the carbon surface with catalysts like metallic oxides or metallic nanoparticles. On the other hand, covalent functionalization involves covalently attaching chemical groups on the surface of these carbon-based materials [Fig. 3
                     ].

Having a high concentration of ammonia in the environment serves as a hazardous health concern for the health of all living organisms. Direct exposure to about 500 ppm of NH3 leads to severe irritation in the oral and nasal passages, resulting in pulmonary edema in human beings [64] Exposure to lower concentrations can also cause skin irritation, impairment of the respiratory system, and harmful effects on the eyes. Fertilizers and animal products (agronomic processes) are the primary sources of ammonia. The Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set the permissible level of ammonia exposure at 25 to 50 ppm for about 8 hours. Ammonia in water has also been declared as noxious. Both its forms, NH3 and NH4
                           +, are environmental pollutants [65] They are a serious threat to both aquatic life and the ecosystem. Similarly, NO2 (nitrogen dioxide) is very dangerous for humans and the environment [Fig. 10
                           ]. Acid rain and photochemical smog are the consequences of NO2 in the atmosphere. The exhaust of automobiles and processes like combustion release large amounts of NO2 into the atmosphere. Asthma and irritation of the respiratory tracts are some of the ill effects of NO2 seen in humans. The maximum amount of NO2 to which it is safe to be exposed is 5 ppm for 8 hrs. Concentrations higher than 5 ppm of NO2 pose serious risks [66]
